Italy clinched qualification for Euro 2008 with a pulsating 2-1 victory over Scotland at Hampden Park. A series of wildfires in Southern California have scorched over 400,000 acres and forced hundreds of thousands of people to evacuate their homes. The fires have killed one person and injured at least 70 more. Firefighters are facing wind-whipped flames and have been aided by resources from Mexico, the state, and federal governments, as well as inmates from California's prisons. San Diego Fire Department Battalion Chief Bruce Cartelli described the scenes as "utter devastation" with hundreds of homes lost and "many hundreds" damaged. The fires are expected to continue until the winds turn around or reach the ocean. President Bush is scheduled to visit the area on Thursday.

In an interview with John Defterios of CNN, Sallie Krawcheck, Chairman and CEO of Citi Global Wealth Management, discusses the movement of capital outside of the G8 countries and the potential shift in economic activity from developed economies to emerging markets such as the Middle East and Asia. Krawcheck believes that New York is losing its status as a financial capital of the world due to factors such as high taxes, litigious environment, and over-regulation of sovereign funds. She also notes that the growth potential of emerging markets such as China and the Middle East is significant, and that Wall Street may be ready for a woman to run a money center bank.

A fire official has confirmed that the Santiago Fire in Orange County, California was started by someone with knowledge of arson. The fire, which has burned over 25,000 acres and destroyed at least 22 structures, was started in two places along a little-traveled road. The evidence found at the scene indicates that the fire was intentionally set, and the reward for information leading to an arrest has increased to $250,000. The California Department of Forestry and Fire Protection said the fire was only 30% contained Thursday morning, and investigators are looking into whether a man arrested on suspicion of arson in the San Fernando Valley may have had a role in any of the ongoing blazes. In San Bernardino County, John Alfred Rund was arrested and charged with setting a small fire, and Anthony Riperti was arrested and charged with starting a fire in Redlands. The San Diego County Sheriff's Department also arrested an adult and a juvenile accused of starting a fire in Vista.

The wildfires in Southern California have caused significant destruction and loss of life, with 500 homes lost in the mountainous region of San Bernardino County and 1,664 structures destroyed overall, including 1,436 homes. The fires have killed three people and injured 40, and have burned over 434,543 acres, or about 10 times the size of Washington, D.C. The largest fire, the Witch fire, is now 10% contained, and seven other fires are also contained. The FBI and the Orange County Fire Authority are investigating the Santiago fire, which has burned over 19,000 acres and is suspected to be an arson. The cost of homes destroyed by the wildfires is likely to top $1 billion in San Diego County alone. Federal help has arrived, including a major disaster declaration signed by President Bush, which will speed federal dollars to people whose property losses aren't covered by insurance and will help local and state agencies pay for the emergency response. Evacuees can go online to apply for federal help at FEMA.gov.

A Sudanese court found a British teacher, Gillian Gibbons, guilty of insulting religion and sentenced her to 15 days in prison for allowing her students to name a teddy bear "Mohammed." Gibbons, 54, was arrested Sunday and faced charges under Article 125 of Sudan's constitution, which relates to insulting religion and inciting hatred. Although there is no ban on images of Allah or the Prophet Mohammed in the Quran, likenesses are considered highly offensive by Muslims. The Foreign Office expressed Britain's dissatisfaction with the verdict and stated that they will continue to provide consular assistance to Gibbons. The teacher could have faced a sentence of 40 lashes, a fine, or a jail term of up to a year.

Seven college students died in a weekend fire at a beach house in Ocean Isle Beach, North Carolina. The fire occurred early Sunday morning and engulfed the house in flames, leaving little more than the framing intact. The victims were identified as six University of South Carolina students and a Clemson University student. Six other South Carolina students were able to escape the house in time, but one of them, Chip Auman's 18-year-old daughter, was hospitalized due to smoke inhalation complications. The cause of the fire is still under investigation, but authorities do not believe foul play was involved. The university community is offering support and counseling to students affected by the tragedy.

Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez has announced that he is cutting all ties with Colombia as long as current President Alvaro Uribe is in office. Chavez had been mediating efforts to secure the release of hostages held by the FARC and ELN rebels, but Uribe ended Chavez's participation without notice, citing protocol violations. Chavez accused Uribe of lying and bowing to pressure from Washington to "get rid of Chavez." Despite this, Chavez expressed his willingness to help the Colombian people.

Ann Curley, a type I diabetic, shares her personal story of living with diabetes for 40 years. She recounts how she was diagnosed at the age of 7 by Dr. Robert Deputy, who taught her how to test her urine for sugar, give herself injections of insulin, and follow a diabetic diet. Despite the challenges, Curley views her diagnosis as a blessing in disguise, as it forced her family to eat healthily and taught her about good nutrition. She also discusses the advancements in diabetes technology, including home blood glucose testing kits, insulin pumps, and continuous glucose monitors. Curley participated in clinical trials for three different CGM devices and found them all to be accurate. She hopes to live another 40 years and is grateful for the progress made in diabetes technology.

Former Wales and British Lions center Ray Gravell has passed away at the age of 56 due to a suspected heart attack. Gravell won 23 caps for Wales and played on the Lions tour of South Africa in 1980. He made his debut for Wales in 1975 and was known for his passion, flair, and dignity on the field. After retiring as a player in 1985, Gravell became president of Llanelli RFC and the Llanelli Scarlets, and also pursued a career as an actor and rugby broadcaster. Earlier this year, Gravell had his right leg amputated below the knee due to complications linked with his diabetes, but he had been recovering well. The Welsh Rugby Union (WRU) has praised Gravell as an ambassador for rugby and Wales, and a great example of how the game can bring out the best in a person.

Barack Obama's presidential campaign is facing controversy after it was revealed that one of the performers at an upcoming gospel concert in South Carolina, Donnie McClurkin, has made statements against the LGBTQ+ community. McClurkin has said that homosexuality is a choice and that he was "once involved with those desires and those thoughts" but was able to overcome them through prayer. This has sparked criticism from gay and lesbian leaders and bloggers, who argue that Obama is "sucking up to anti-gay bigots" by inviting McClurkin to perform. In response, Obama's campaign has issued a statement saying that he strongly disagrees with McClurkin's views and will continue to fight for LGBTQ+ rights as president. However, the controversy has raised questions about Obama's ability to unite disparate voting blocs under his umbrella of "change."

Atletico Madrid defeated Real Zaragoza 4-0 in the Spanish Primera Liga, with Luis Garcia scoring his first goal for the club and Diego Forlan adding a brace. Getafe also picked up their first win of the season with a 2-0 victory over Murcia, while Valladolid suffered a 2-1 defeat against Athletic Bilbao.

The company, Las Vegas Sands Corp., owns several properties in Las Vegas and Macau, including The Venetian Resort Hotel Casino and the Sands Expo and Convention Center in Las Vegas, and the Sands Macau in Macau. The Venetian Casino Resort opened in 1999 and has since received recognition for revolutionizing the hotel industry in Las Vegas. The property has 3,014 suites, 18 restaurants, and a retail mall with canals and gondolas. In 2004, the company opened the Sands Macau in China, which includes gaming facilities, luxury suites, and an international VIP club. The company went public in December 2004 with a successful initial public offering. The Venetian is one of the most productive properties on the Las Vegas Strip, with an occupancy rate of 98.3% and an average daily room rate of $219.

The US Secretary of State, Condoleezza Rice, has announced that State Department officials should serve where they are needed, including in war-torn Iraq. This comes after a contentious town hall-style meeting where foreign service officers objected to the possibility of "directed assignments" in Iraq. Rice said that the State Department is facing a shortage of personnel in Iraq and that 15 people have stepped forward to volunteer for service since the new policy was announced. She emphasized that the assignments are new positions and that the State Department has been successful in filling jobs in Iraq with volunteers. However, she also acknowledged that there are risks involved in serving in a war zone and that the State Department is doing everything it can to protect its diplomats.

At least seven deaths have been attributed to the wildfires in Southern California, including four bodies found in a canyon east of San Diego. Over 9,000 firefighters are battling the blazes, which have scorched 472,478 acres (738 square miles) of land, an area roughly three-quarters of the size of Rhode Island. The cost of homes destroyed by the wildfires is likely to top $1 billion in San Diego County alone. Federal help has been promised to those affected by the fires, and evacuations have been ordered in several communities. Arson investigations are under way in connection with some of the wildfires.

The commander of the USS Hampton, Cmdr. Michael B. Portland, has been relieved of his command due to a loss of confidence in his ability to lead the crew. This comes after an investigation into misconduct by crew members, including falsifying inspection records for the cooling system of the ship's nuclear reactor. Six personnel have been punished for their actions, and one officer and two enlisted crew members have been temporarily reassigned to Submarine Squadron 11. The misconduct was discovered on September 17, and a fact-finding investigation is ongoing. The USS Hampton remains in port in San Diego, California, with a crew of 13 officers and 116 enlisted personnel.

A bus crashed into a pickup truck and an 18-wheeler on a highway in Arkansas, killing the pickup driver and two bus riders. Forty people were injured in the crash, which shut down a 13-mile stretch of Interstate-40. The bus was traveling from Chicago to Dallas when the accident occurred. The driver of the bus and the driver of the 18-wheeler suffered minor injuries, while two passengers were found dead inside the bus. The names of the deceased have not been released.

Kelly Pless, a 31-year-old graduate student from Sunny Isles Beach, Florida, struggled with her weight for most of her adult life. She reached her breaking point when she had trouble breathing and doctors told her that her weight was to blame. Despite her doubts, Pless decided to take action and started walking and running to lose weight. She adopted an "eat to live" philosophy and focused on portion control and satisfying her cravings with fruit. Pless has lost 95 pounds and kept it off for 1½ years, and has set a new professional goal to pursue a doctorate in food and exercise psychology to help others who are battling obesity and eating disorders. Running has become a constant for Pless and has done more for her than maintain her weight, which is now about 125 pounds.

The Singapore Airlines A380, the world's largest commercial jet, made its maiden passenger journey between Singapore and Sydney this week, two years late and billions of dollars over budget. The aircraft features "beyond first class" cabins with private suites, double beds, and luxury amenities. The airline has opted for a configuration that offers luxury while generating revenue, rather than offering casinos, gyms, and showers like some other airlines. The A380 has a quiet engine, low fuel-burn, and can carry 40% more passengers than other large aircraft. The airline has ordered 19 superjumbos and will commence scheduled service between Singapore and Sydney on one of the three daily flights in each direction. The A380 will also be used on one of the three daily flights between Singapore and London's Heathrow Airport.

The illegal export of US military technology to Iran and China is a growing concern, according to the Justice Department. The department plans to tighten monitoring of export licenses and increase restrictions on technologies that could pose a danger to US national security. Recent prosecutions have highlighted illegal exports of stealth missile technology, military aircraft components, and other restricted technology destined for China or Iran. Two recent cases include a Pittsburgh company sentenced for lying about an illegal export of products that can be used in nuclear reactions and in the nose cones of ballistic missiles, and two men charged last week with attempting to illegally export restricted components for F-4 and F-14 fighter jets, with F-14 components highly sought after by Iran, the only military in the world still flying the jet.

The article discusses the visit of King Abdullah of Saudi Arabia to London and the strong trading and business relationship between the two countries. Saudi Arabia is the UK's largest trading partner in the Middle East and the UK is the second largest foreign investor in the Kingdom. The article concludes that despite any political sensitivity surrounding the visit, the relationship between the two nations is far deeper and the opportunities for businessmen are immense.

Tens of thousands of Congolese refugees fled camps in the Democratic Republic of Congo on Tuesday as rebel troops attacked government forces in the area. The UNHCR reported that about 28,000 refugees abandoned the first three camps, while about 2,000 left a fourth camp. The agency identified the affected camps as Mugunga I, Mugunga II, Lac Vert and Bulengo. The UNHCR stated that 375,000 Congolese in North Kivu province have been forced from their homes in the past year, with 160,000 fleeing their homes in the past two months amid ongoing fighting between renegade troops and government forces.

Genarlow Wilson, a 21-year-old man who was released from prison last week after serving two years of a 10-year sentence for aggravated child molestation, rejected a plea deal from prosecutors despite it potentially releasing him from prison months earlier. Wilson explained that the prospect of being labeled a sex offender and not being able to have a family of his own in the future drove him to turn down the deal. He was convicted of having oral sex with a 15-year-old girl at a New Year's Eve party in 2003 when he was 17 years old, and the conviction carried a 10-year mandatory prison sentence and a sex offender designation. The state Legislature amended the law under which Wilson was convicted, making such sexual encounters misdemeanors, but the Legislature did not make the law retroactive, so it had no effect on Wilson's sentence. The state Supreme Court ruled 4-3 that Wilson's sentence "constitutes cruel and unusual punishment" and he was released from prison. Wilson is focused on the future and hopes to soon immerse himself in his college studies, majoring in sociology. He stated that he will be more conservative, more alert, and more appreciative of the blessings bestowed upon him, and he does not want to see the inside of a prison again.

The confirmation of Michael Mukasey as Attorney General is likely, despite concerns about his views on "waterboarding" and the president's power to order electronic surveillance. Two key Democratic senators, Dianne Feinstein and Charles Schumer, have announced their support for Mukasey's nomination, while Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Patrick Leahy has announced he will vote against it. Leahy and other Democrats have expressed concerns about Mukasey's views on torture and the separation of powers, while Feinstein and Schumer argue that Mukasey is the best available candidate and that voting him down would only perpetuate acting and recess appointments. Despite these concerns, President Bush has demanded the Senate confirm Mukasey, citing the need for a full national security team in place during a time of war.

Nine people were killed and 19 injured when a tour bus carrying people on a ski trip left a highway and rolled over in southeastern Utah. The bus was traveling from Telluride, Colorado to Phoenix, Arizona when it crashed on state Highway 163, about five miles north of Mexican Hat, at 7:30 pm (9:30 pm ET). The bus lost control on a curve, ran off the road and rolled over several times, tumbling 41 feet down an embankment. The roof of the bus split open and multiple occupants were ejected. Rescue crews took the injured to hospitals in Utah, Colorado and Arizona. Four of the dead were male and five were female, and most of the passengers were returning home from a weekend ski trip to Telluride.

Banksy is a British street artist known for his subversive and satirical public art. He has gained international recognition for his stencil works that often depict political and social commentary. Despite his popularity and high-profile sales, his identity remains a mystery. Banksy's work has been met with both praise and criticism, with some viewing it as vandalism and others as public art. His latest piece in East London has sparked controversy, with a passer-by claiming to have taken a photo of the artist at work.

The garbage crisis in Naples, Italy has been ongoing for over a decade, with the region's dumps reaching full capacity and a state of emergency being declared every year. Despite the allocation of €1.8 billion in emergency funds, the problem has not been solved, with incinerators that were supposed to be built remaining unfinished and allegations of mafia involvement. The local mafia, known as the Camorra, is believed to be profiting from the crisis, with companies linked to the underworld disposing of waste in the open or at regular city dumps. The government has proposed re-opening a previously shut dump to dispose of 3,700 tons of waste that is currently lying in the streets of Naples and surrounding areas, but this has sparked protests from residents who were promised that a golf course would be built on the site instead.

Russia has resumed regular flights of its strategic bombers beyond its borders, with 14 aircraft taking off simultaneously from different airfields across the country. This move is seen as a response to security threats and a sign of Russia's growing assertiveness, with some Western military leaders viewing it as a form of "chest-pounding" to demonstrate Russia's military capabilities. The flights are likely to add to concerns about Russia's increasing assertiveness, particularly in light of recent tensions between Russia and the West over issues such as Kosovo, energy, and Russia's treatment of its ex-Soviet neighbors.

1. The Hamburger: Louis' Lunch in New Haven, Connecticut is credited as the birthplace of the hamburger, with the story going that a rushed businessman asked owner Louis Lassen for something quick to eat on the run, and Lassen cooked up a beef patty and served it between bread.
2. The Fried Twinkie: At The ChipShop in Brooklyn, New York, owner Christopher Sell invented the fried Twinkie by freezing the snack, dipping it in batter, and deep-frying it.
3. Root Beer Float: In 1893, a failed gold-miner-turned-soda-company-owner named Frank J. Wisner was drinking a bottle of his Myers Avenue Red root beer while looking up at Cow Mountain in Colorado, and he had the idea to float a scoop of vanilla ice cream in the root beer.
4. Corn Dogs: In 1946, Ed Waldmire, Jr. debuted the Cozy Dog -- the first corn dog on a stick -- at his restaurant in Springfield, Illinois.
5. The Pizzeria: Gennaro Lombardi opened a small grocery store in New York City's Little Italy in 1905, which later became the first true pizzeria in America after an employee named Anthony "Totonno" Pero started selling pizzas out of the back.
6. Fat Darrell: At R.U. Hungry in New Brunswick, New Jersey, a hungry student named Darrell W. Butler convinced a vendor to put chicken fingers, mozzarella sticks, French fries, and marinara sauce on a sandwich, which became known as the Fat Darrell.
7. Philly Cheesesteak: Pat's King Of Steaks in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania is credited as the birthplace of the Philly cheesesteak, with the story going that hot dog stand owners Pasquale (Pat) and Harry Olivieri added onions to their steak sandwiches in 1932.
8. Onion Rings: According to Pig Stand in Dallas, Texas, a careless cook accidentally dropped an onion slice in batter and pulled it out and tossed it in the fryer, creating the onion ring.
9. Derby Pie: At Melrose Inn in Prospect, Kentucky, manager George Kern created derby pie in the mid-1950s with help from his parents, Walter and Leaudra, and the dessert was such a hit that the family was soon baking the treat full-time.

Authorities in Azerbaijan have uncovered a terror plot against the US Embassy in the capital city of Baku, prompting the embassy to close its doors to the public. The plot was unraveled after a weekend raid outside Baku that netted several suspected members of a radical Islamic group. The group had planned to attack the embassy and government buildings, but no specific individuals were targeted. The US State Department has issued a warden message warning Americans in Azerbaijan to take precautions and maintain a high level of vigilance. US authorities are working closely with their counterparts in Baku to determine when normal embassy operations will resume.

A North Korean freighter was hijacked by pirates off the coast of Somalia, but the crew was able to regain control of the ship after a deadly battle. The USS James E. Williams, a US Navy destroyer, responded to reports of the hijacking and ordered the pirates to give up their weapons. When the crew of the Dai Hong Dan stormed the bridge, a fierce battle ensued, resulting in the deaths of two pirates and the injury of three crew members. The remaining pirates were captured and are being held aboard the North Korean vessel. This is the second incident of piracy reported in recent days, with a second US Navy destroyer searching for pirates who hijacked a Japanese-owned ship. The US and North Korea have no diplomatic relations, and the incident highlights the ongoing problem of piracy in the region.

Debra Lafave, a former Florida middle school teacher convicted of having sex with a student, violated her probation by hugging a young co-worker. Lafave was arrested after talking with a teenager and is not allowed to have contact with anyone under 18. Although the judge did not send her to jail, saying the violation was "not willful and substantial," Lafave was ordered to quit her restaurant job and is now working as a receptionist in her mother's beauty shop. Lafave has a history of bipolar disorder and is receiving treatment.

Ralph Lauren is a fashion designer who has been in the industry for 40 years and has had a significant impact on the way people dress and live. He is known for his classic, luxurious designs and his ability to create a consistent image across his brand. Lauren believes that the key to longevity in the fashion industry is to keep doing what you do best and to get your message out to the consumer. He has a global reach and has expanded his brand to include stores in many countries, including China and Japan. Lauren is confident that there is still room for growth and expansion, despite the fast-paced and ever-changing nature of the fashion industry.

A suspect in the fatal shooting of a Philadelphia police officer has been captured in Miami, Florida. John Lewis, 27, was taken into custody without incident at a homeless shelter where he was found praying with a Bible. Lewis is suspected of shooting Officer Chuck Cassidy on October 31, who died the next day. Investigators say Lewis was spotted on security video boarding a bus to Miami on Saturday night. Former co-workers of Lewis are surprised by the allegations against him, describing him as "nice." Lewis has a history of drug arrests, with cases still pending.

If you're a first-time car buyer looking for a stylish and affordable vehicle, consider the following options:

President Bush criticized the Democratic-controlled Congress for not getting its work done and wasting time on investigations and failed votes to pull troops out of Iraq. He also criticized Congress for not sending him a single appropriations bill and for trying to "hold hostage" funding for troops. Democrats fired back, accusing Bush of being the biggest obstacle to extending health coverage to 10 million low-income children and of breaking a promise he made in 2004 to extend coverage under the SCHIP program. They also accused the Bush administration of being fiscally irresponsible and adding to the national debt. The Senate could vote on the children's health bill as early as Tuesday.

Lee Boyd Malvo, the sniper who terrorized the Washington area in 2002, is still grappling with shame, guilt, and remorse according to a letter he wrote to CNN. He is serving a life sentence at Virginia's toughest prison and spends 23 hours a day in his cell. A social worker who has worked extensively with him, Carmeta Albarus-Lindo, has said that Malvo is a changed person since his arrest and conviction. Malvo was brainwashed by his surrogate father, John Allen Muhammad, into committing the murders. However, some investigators were horrified when a Virginia jury spared Malvo's life. The victims' families are content with the jury's verdict, and Malvo will never forgive himself for what happened. Muhammad, Malvo's surrogate father, is still fighting on death row and wants to correct inaccurate statements made by the media about his relationship with Malvo.

Italy national coach Roberto Donadoni has named a 23-man squad for next Saturday's Euro 2008 qualifier against Scotland, including striker Cristiano Lucarelli who scored twice against South Africa. The squad also includes the return of captain Fabio Cannavaro from suspension. Italy are currently third in Group B, two points behind leaders France and one point below Scotland.

Erik Prince, the CEO and chairman of Blackwater USA, appeared before the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform to address an FBI investigation into a September 16 shootout involving Blackwater personnel in Iraq that resulted in the deaths of Iraqi civilians. Prince stated that Blackwater is a company of dedicated professionals who provide training to the military and law enforcement communities and risk their lives to protect Americans overseas. He emphasized that Blackwater personnel are all military and law enforcement veterans and that the company shares the committee's interest in ensuring accountability and oversight of contract personnel supporting U.S. operations. Prince also provided information on the company's operations in Iraq, including that Blackwater reports to the embassy's regional security officer and that the company does not engage in offensive or military missions but performs only defensive security functions. He concluded by stating that Blackwater welcomes the FBI review announced yesterday and will cooperate fully.

UEFA has banned Benfica midfielder Augustin Binya for six matches following a horror tackle on Celtic's Scott Brown. Binya was sent off for the challenge in their Champions League match last week, which seriously endangered Brown's physical health. Benfica can appeal the ban, which will rule Binya out of their remaining Group D matches and potentially future matches in the Champions League or UEFA Cup. Brown has been passed fit for Scotland's Euro 2008 qualifier against Italy. This is the second time this season that UEFA has had to intervene following an incident involving Celtic, with AC Milan keeper Dida being handed a one-match ban for collapsing theatrically when a fan of the Scottish club invaded the pitch.

In a recent CNN/Opinion Research Corporation poll, Sen. Hillary Clinton (D-NY) remains the front-runner for the Democratic presidential nomination, with 44% of likely Democratic voters supporting her. Clinton's closest rival, Sen. Barack Obama (D-IL), received 25% of the vote. Former Sen. John Edwards (D-NC) came in third with 14%. Russian President Vladimir Putin visited Tehran, Iran on Tuesday, where he met with Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad and other leaders of Caspian Sea nations. Putin stated that Iran should be allowed to pursue its nuclear program for peaceful purposes, and that Russia is cooperating with Iranian nuclear agencies to achieve this goal. He also emphasized that no Caspian nation should offer its territory to third parties for military action against other Caspian states. Putin's visit is the first by a Kremlin leader to Iran since 1943, and is seen as a show of Russia's independence in global affairs.

Three French journalists were released from custody in Chad, hours after French President Nicolas Sarkozy held emergency talks with Chadian President Idriss Deby. The journalists were among seven Europeans released by a Chadian judge, including a Spanish flight crew. The release comes after workers from the French-based charity Zoe's Ark were accused of trying to fly 103 children out of Chad in a kidnapping and adoption operation. The children may never return to their families due to the difficulty in determining their backgrounds, according to the Red Cross. Six members of the French charity, four Chadians, and four remaining members of the flight crew face kidnapping and fraud charges. The leader of Zoe's Ark testified that the three journalists and the flight crew were not involved in the alleged plot. The three journalists were initially charged with complicity in the alleged kidnapping attempt, but it's not clear if the charges have been dropped.

A Black Hawk helicopter carrying 11 US military personnel crashed in northeastern Italy, killing 4 people and injuring 7, including 2 who later died. The helicopter, attached to the 1st Battalion, 214th Aviation Regiment, crashed near the Piave River north of Treviso, between the towns of Maserata Sul Piave and Santa Lucia Di Piave. The US military is not releasing the names of the victims, pending notification of their families. The helicopter is considered the workhorse of the military's helicopter fleet and has been used in missions in Iraq and Afghanistan to carry troops and equipment.

Three men have been arrested and charged with murder in the shooting death of a University of Memphis football player, Taylor Bradford. The 21-year-old victim was found fatally wounded near the campus residence hall area after a car crash on September 30. The suspects, DeeShawn Tate, Victor Trezevant, and Courtney Washington, were charged with murder in perpetration of attempted aggravated robbery. According to Memphis Police Department Director Larry Godwin, the three men were arrested with the help of a citizen's tip and Crimestoppers, and the investigation is ongoing. The suspects are not students at the university, and prosecutors are considering seeking the death penalty in the case.

A court has ordered Britney Spears to give up custody of her two children to her ex-husband, Kevin Federline, effective Wednesday at noon. Federline will retain custody of the children "until further order of the court." The decision comes after Spears was found to have engaged in "habitual, frequent, and continuous use of controlled substances and alcohol" and after a bitter custody fight between the exes. The court has also ordered Spears to spend eight hours per week working with a "parenting coach" and to avoid alcohol or "other non-prescription controlled substances" 12 hours before taking custody of the children.

Former football star O.J. Simpson was released from jail on Wednesday after posting $250,000 bail. Simpson had been in jail since January 11 after prosecutors alleged he violated the terms of his bail by attempting to contact a co-defendant. At a hearing on Wednesday, a judge doubled Simpson's bail to ensure his appearance at an April 7 trial and scolded him for not taking the matter seriously. Simpson posted bail at about 6:15 pm local time and was released from jail. The judge also imposed strict conditions on Simpson's release, including no contact with victims, witnesses, or co-defendants, and no phone messages to third parties. Simpson faces trial on 12 criminal counts, including conspiracy, kidnapping, robbery, burglary, coercion, and assault with a deadly weapon.

The US Air Force has returned F-15E Strike Eagle jets to service over Iraq and Afghanistan after grounding other F-15 models following a crash in Missouri. The F-15Es will undergo inspections of critical parts on the airframe before returning to flying missions. The rest of the almost 500 F-15s will remain grounded until the investigation into the crash is complete. The F-15E is the youngest and most sophisticated in the F-15 inventory and is heavily used by Central Command for ground support in the U.S.-led wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.

Former detainees of Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) have accused the agency of forcibly injecting them with psychotropic drugs while trying to deport them. Two immigrants, Raymond Soeoth and Amadou Diouf, are plaintiffs in a class-action lawsuit brought by the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) against the government.
